First, note that

\begin{align*}-\sin\left(\frac1{n}\right) \leq (-1)^n \sin\left(\frac1{n}\right) \leq \sin\left(\frac1{n}\right)\end{align*}

Further, since

\begin{align*}\lim_{n \to \infty} \frac1{n} = 0\end{align*}

and $\displaystyle \sin x$ is continuous at 0,

\begin{align*}\lim_{n \to \infty} \sin\left(\frac1{n}\right) = \sin\left(\lim_{n \to \infty} \frac1{n}\right) = \sin(0) = 0\end{align*}

Similarly,

\begin{align*}\lim_{n \to \infty} -\sin\left(\frac1{n}\right) = -0 = 0.\end{align*}

By the squeeze theorem,

\begin{align*}\lim_{n \to \infty} (-1)^n \sin\left(\frac1{n}\right)\end{align*}

exists and equals 0 as well.
